'''Notorious markets''' is a term used in the United States to describe websites and physical markets where large-scale [[intellectual property]] infringement takes place.
==History== Since 2006,<ref>{{cite web|title=USTR Announces Results of Special 301 Review of Notorious Markets|url=http://www.ustr.gov/about-us/press-office/press-releases/2011/december/ustr-announces-results-special-301-review-notorio|accessdate=2 December 2014}}</ref> the members of the [[International Intellectual Property Alliance]] in conjunction with the [[Office of the United States Trade Representative]] has annually filed a list of Notorious Markets<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ernesto|title=MPAA Reports The Pirate Bay to The U.S. Government|url=http://torrentfreak.com/mpaa-reports-top-pirate-sites-u-s-government-141027/|accessdate=2 December 2014|date=October 27, 2014}}</ref> as a part of their [[Special 301 Report]] to the [[Federal government of the United States|U.S. federal government]]. It lists virtual markets (websites) and physical markets outside of the US where large scale [[copyright infringement]] takes place and recommends trade sanctions for countries with weak copyright protection enforcement. Since 2010 the list is separately issued as a part of an out-of-cycle review between the main report submissions.<ref>{{cite web|title=2014 Special 301 Out-of-Cycle Review of Notorious Markets: Request for Public Comments|url=https://www.federalregister.gov/articles/2014/09/26/2014-22904/2014-special-301-out-of-cycle-review-of-notorious-markets-request-for-public-comments|accessdate=13 December 2014}}</ref>
Whilst the list of markets does not directly form national trade policy: {{quote|The United States encourages the responsible authorities to step up efforts to combat piracy and counterfeiting in these and similar markets|sign=Notorious Markets Report<ref name=report06 />}}
